Broome County Regression Analysis

Amber Jacobson

December 6, 2017

Social Equity in Relation to Owner-Occupied Housing

In order to assess equity within the county, a number of variables from census information can be used to assess which factors are significant when it comes to a persons ability to own a home. My hypothesis is that age, income, and education are the significant variables. In this analysis, multiple regression will be used to see the relevance of the selected variables.

Part 1

Create a map of Broome County census tracts as well as a map of the level of owner-occupancy across the census tracts.

if(!require(tmap)) {install.packages("tmap")}
library(tmap)

qtm(Broome)

qtm(Broome, fill="JNUE014")

The color scheme of the map makes it difficult to analyze where the concentration of owner-occupied housing is, but if the map is looked at carefully it is possible to identify that the lowest concentration of owner-occupied housing is in the more urban areas of the city of Binghamton and towns of Endicott and Johnson City.

Part 2A

First Regression

Perform a regression analysis using owner-occupied housing units as the dependent variable with age, income, and education attainment as independent variables.

owner.occupied <- df$JNUE014
age <- df$JL0M001
income <- df$ADOVE001
education <- df$ADMZE001

bc <- cbind(owner.occupied,age,income,education)
colnames(bc) <- c("Owner Occupied", "Age", "Income", "Education")
x <- as.data.frame(bc)
m <- lm(x$`Owner Occupied` ~ x$Age + x$Income + x$Education)
anova(m)
## Analysis of Variance Table
## 
## Response: x$`Owner Occupied`
##             Df Sum Sq Mean Sq F value   Pr(>F)   
## x$Age        1   34.3   34.33  0.1841 0.669683   
## x$Income     1  994.2  994.17  5.3315 0.025030 * 
## x$Education  1 1434.9 1434.90  7.6951 0.007717 **
## Residuals   51 9509.9  186.47                    
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

Based off of the ANOVA table, education attainment and income are significant variables in relation to owner-occupied housing. The P-value of age is greater than .5, thus proving that it is not as useful in the regression. Age isnt significant so this may be a weakness in the analysis and should perhaps be left out.

Part 2B

Perform a backwards regression analysis to confirm the variables that should be included in the final equation.

Part 3A

Second Regression

Perform another regression analysis. Do not include age, but instead include level of education attainment at different levels (high school, Associates, Bachelors, Masters). Analyze how this changes the ANOVA Table.

highschool <- df$ADMZE017
associates <- df$ADMZE021
bachelors <- df$ADMZE022
masters <- df$ADMZE023

bc2 <- cbind(owner.occupied,income,highschool, associates, bachelors, masters)
colnames(bc2) <- c("Owner Occupied", "Income", "High School", "Associate's", "Bachelor's", "Master's")
y <- as.data.frame(bc2)
str(y)
## 'data.frame':    55 obs. of  6 variables:
##  $ Owner Occupied: int  5 26 15 4 3 52 33 6 49 9 ...
##  $ Income        : int  35 30 31 26 21 29 45 24 13 14 ...
##  $ High School   : int  11 33 13 14 12 21 50 15 10 7 ...
##  $ Associate's   : int  17 10 8 19 52 7 16 51 1 50 ...
##  $ Bachelor's    : int  20 9 16 4 44 48 21 52 36 2 ...
##  $ Master's      : int  18 8 47 35 31 40 13 28 9 23 ...
m2 <- lm(y$`Owner Occupied` ~ y$Income + y$`High School` + y$`Associate's` + y$`Bachelor's` + y$`Master's`)
anova(m2)
## Analysis of Variance Table
## 
## Response: y$`Owner Occupied`
##                 Df Sum Sq Mean Sq F value  Pr(>F)   
## y$Income         1 1016.8 1016.78  6.0986 0.01706 * 
## y$`High School`  1  988.8  988.83  5.9310 0.01856 * 
## y$`Associate's`  1   87.7   87.73  0.5262 0.47165   
## y$`Bachelor's`   1 1698.4 1698.35 10.1867 0.00247 **
## y$`Master's`     1   12.3   12.27  0.0736 0.78735   
## Residuals       49 8169.4  166.72                   
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

This regression indicates that income as well as completion of high school are significant factors in owner-occupancy rates. Attainment of a Bachelors degree is a slightly more significant variable while having an Associates or obtaining a Masters are insignificant.

m2.reduced <- step(m2, direction="backward")

When completing the backwards regression analysis, this model suggests to include all variables except that of the Masters degree. Although the Associates degree component was not marked with a * for significance, its P-value is still less than .5 so it cannot be excluded from the regression. It would appear that obtaining a graduate level degree has little to no impact on owning a home in Broome County.

Part 4

The first two regression analysis only dealt with non-family owner-occupied households. Perform another regression analysis on married couple owner-occupied households and see if the results vary from the first regression analysis. Then, run the analysis backwards as we did in the first two analyses.

married.households <- df$JNUE004 

bc3 <- cbind(married.households,age,income,education)
colnames(bc3) <- c("Married - Owner Occupied", "Age", "Income", "Education")
x <- as.data.frame(bc3)
m3 <- lm(x$`Married - Owner Occupied` ~ x$Age + x$Income + x$Education)

For this analysis, it seems that none of the independent variables impact the owner-occupancy rate of married couples. All P-values are greater than .5. This may be because it is easier for people with spouses to buy houses due to usually having two sources of income.

Part 5

Perform a regression analysis on single mother households (owner-occupied) and see if that makes a difference when compared to married couple households.

single.mother <- df$JNUE011

bc4 <- cbind(single.mother,age,income,education)
colnames(bc4) <- c("Single Mother", "Age", "Income", "Education")
z <- as.data.frame(bc4)
m4 <- lm(z$`Single Mother` ~ z$Age + z$Income + z$Education)
anova(m4)
## Analysis of Variance Table
## 
## Response: z$`Single Mother`
##             Df Sum Sq Mean Sq F value    Pr(>F)    
## z$Age        1  113.4  113.42  0.7626 0.3865956    
## z$Income     1 2096.7 2096.74 14.0982 0.0004461 ***
## z$Education  1  364.6  364.64  2.4518 0.1235750    
## Residuals   51 7584.9  148.72                      
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
m4.reduced <- step(m4, direction ="backward")
## Start:  AIC=278.96
## z$`Single Mother` ~ z$Age + z$Income + z$Education
## 
##               Df Sum of Sq    RSS    AIC
## - z$Age        1     96.48 7681.4 277.66
## <none>                     7584.9 278.96
## - z$Education  1    364.64 7949.5 279.55

## Step:  AIC=277.66

## 
##               Df Sum of Sq    RSS    AIC
## - z$Education  1    276.69 7958.1 277.60
## <none>                     7681.4 277.66
## - z$Income     1   1519.73 9201.1 285.59
## 
## Step:  AIC=277.6
## z$`Single Mother` ~ z$Income
## 
##            Df Sum of Sq     RSS    AIC
## <none>                   7958.1 277.60
## - z$Income  1    2201.6 10159.7 289.04

In this regression, it appears that income is the most significant variable when it comes to a single mothers ability to own a home in Broome County. This makes sense as there is no second income to rely on. Age and education factor in somewhat, but in relation to the low P-value of the income variable they are not as significant.

Conclusion

Income and education, which are closely related to social equity, are the most significant variables related to owner-occupancy rates in non-family households.

Work Cited

Steve Manson, Jonathan Schroeder, David Van Riper, and Steven Ruggles. IPUMS National Historical Geographic Information System: Version 12.0 [Database]. Minneapolis: University of Minnesota, 2017. http://doi.org/10.18128/D050.V12.0
